05607nam a2200685Ia 9780801461729DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20112015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014617297 a10.7591/97808014617292doi  a(DE-B1597)480030  a(OCoLC)979575519  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aF157.W9bM75 2007eb 7aHIS0360802bisacsh04a974.8/012221 aMoyer, Paul B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWild Yankees :bThe Struggle for Independence along Pennsylvania's Revolutionary Frontier /cPaul B. Moyer. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b4 maps, 3 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Terminology -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: A Farmer’s Revolution -- t1. “Among Quarrelsome Yankees, Insidious Indians, and Lonely Wilds”: Natives, Colonists, and the Wyoming Controversy -- t2. “A Great Many Wrangling Disputes”: Authority, Allegiance, Property, and the Frontier War for Independence -- t3. “A Dangerous Combination of Villains”: The Social Context of Agrarian Resistance -- t4. “All the Difficulties of Forming a New Settlement”: Frontier Migration, Land Speculation, and Settler Insurgency -- t5. “A Perfect Union with the People”: Cultures of Resistance along the Revolutionary Frontier -- t6. “Poor and Ignorant but Industrious Settlers”: Frontier Development and the Path to Accommodation -- t7. “Artful Deceivers”: Yankee Notables and the Resolution of the Wyoming Controversy -- tEpilogue: Closing the Revolutionary Frontier -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNortheast Pennsylvania's Wyoming Valley was truly a dark and bloody ground, the site of murders, massacres, and pitched battles. The valley's turbulent history was the product of a bitter contest over property and power known as the Wyoming controversy. This dispute, which raged between the mid-eighteenth and early-nineteenth centuries, intersected with conflicts between whites and native peoples over land, a jurisdictional contest between Pennsylvania and Connecticut, violent contention over property among settlers and land speculators, and the social tumult of the American Revolution. In its later stages, the controversy pitted Pennsylvania and its settlers and speculators against "Wild Yankees"—frontier insurgents from New England who contested the state's authority and soil rights.In Wild Yankees, Paul B. Moyer argues that a struggle for personal independence waged by thousands of ordinary settlers lay at the root of conflict in northeast Pennsylvania and across the revolutionary-era frontier. The concept and pursuit of independence was not limited to actual war or high politics; it also resonated with ordinary people, such as the Wild Yankees, who pursued their own struggles for autonomy. This battle for independence drew settlers into contention with native peoples, wealthy speculators, governments, and each other over land, the shape of America's postindependence social order, and the meaning of the Revolution. With vivid descriptions of the various levels of this conflict, Moyer shows that the Wyoming controversy illuminates settlement, the daily lives of settlers, and agrarian unrest along the early American frontier.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFrontier and pioneer lifexPennsylvaniaxWyoming Valley. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezPennsylvaniazWyoming Valley. 0aIndians of North AmericaxHistoryxPennsylvaniaxWyoming Valley. 0aIndians of North AmericazPennsylvaniazWyoming ValleyxHistory. 0aSusquehanna Claim, 1753-1808. 4aEa